HEADWORD: Rationality
<hw>Ra`tion*al"i*ty</hw> <pr>(r⟦acr⟧sh"⟦ucr⟧n*⟦acr⟧l"⟦icr⟧*t⟦ycr⟧;
277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>-ties</plw>
<pr>(-t⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. <ets>rationalit⟦eacute⟧</ets>, or L.
<ets>rationalitas</ets>.]</ety> <def>The quality or state of being
rational; agreement with reason; possession of reason; due exercise of
reason; reasonableness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When God has made <qex>rationality</qex> the common portion of
mankind, how came it to be thy inclosure?</q> <rj><qau>Gov. of
Tongue.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Well-directed intentions, whose <qex>rationalities</qex> will
never bear a rigid examination.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T.
Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rationalization</ent>⟦br⟧
